<F P=100> AUSTRALASIA </F>
<F P=101> Australia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Government Protests to U.S. on Barley Subsidies </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  BK2502080294 Melbourne Radio Australia in English 0500 GMT 
25 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> BK2502080294 </F>
<F P=104>  Melbourne Radio Australia </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Australia has again protested to the United States 
over the issue of subsidized grain production. John Webster 
reports that the protest was over subsidies for barley 
production. 
  [Begin Webster recording] The Australian Barley Board fears 
the latest subsidy of U.S.$66 per ton will deal a severe blow to 
South Australian and Victorian barley growers. The board's 
general manager, Michael Vanule, says world prices have dropped 
to their lowest in years and the subsidies will only compound 
the problem. The [words indistinct] more worried that the 
Americans and the Europeans are aggressively subsidizing barley 
so soon after the successful end of the GATT talks, which agreed 
on a formula to wind back agricultural subsidies. [end recording] 

</TEXT>

