<F P=100> Thailand </F>
<H3> <TI>   U.S. Action Sought Against Lao Rebel Leader </TI></H3>
<H4>   Editorial: Act Against Vang Pao </H4>
<F P=102> BK2502101294 Bangkok SIAM POST in Thai 25 Feb 94 p 4 </F>
<F P=103> BK2502101294 </F>
<F P=104>  Bangkok SIAM POST </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Thai </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Excerpts] On 23 February, Lieutenant General Thiradet 
Miphian, director of the Supreme Command Intelligence 
Department, petitioned the Police Department to take legal 
action against Generals Vang Pao and Thonglit Chokbengboun of 
the Lao National Liberation Army [LNLA] on charges of violating 
national security. 
  The purpose of the petition is to have the two Lao generals 
investigated in accordance with government policy, because they 
support the organization of illegal movements on Thai territory 
opposing the Lao People's Democratic Republic [LPDR]. The LNLA 
secretly gathered men, weapons, and food supplies in areas of 
Chiang Kham District in Phayao Province and Thung Chang, Mae 
Rim, and Tha Wang Pha Districts in Nan Province to launch 
several armed operations in the LPDR. [passage omitted] 
  In October 1993, the Thai Supreme Command stated that action 
was being taken against some of the 6,096 Lao refugees living at 
Tham Krabok temple in Saraburi Province when it was discovered 
that they were followers of Vang Pao. 
  The Thai Government's harsh policy against Generals Vang Pao 
and Thonglit and their followers -- charging them with national 
security violations and illegal entry -- will help eliminate the 
LPDR Government's suspicions and contribute to stronger 
relations between the two countries. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

