<F P=100> Thailand </F>
<H3> <TI>   Wichit, Prasong Comment on Arms Barter Policy </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  BK2502082294 Bangkok Radio Thailand Network in English 0000 
GMT 25 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> BK2502082294 </F>
<F P=104>  Bangkok Radio Thailand Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Defense Minister Wichit Sukmak has reached 
understanding with military leaders on the government's policy 
of bartering Thai products with foreign weapons. 
  Government spokesman Aphisit Wetchachiwa says the defense 
minister has explained the thinking behind the principle and 
ways and means to proceed in arms deals. Mr. Aphisit says only 
major arms purchases will be subject to barter trade policy. He 
says the government does not intend to interfere in regular 
operation of the Armed Forces and small purchases will not have 
to be negotiated. 
  Foreign Minister Prasong Sunsiri says the Armed Forces' plan 
to buy transport planes from Italy has to be delayed until Italy 
has a new government. 
  Deputy Minister of Commerce Chaiyot Sasomsap also says the 
armed forces should ask Italy to remain committed to the quota 
prices until April as there will be a trade meeting between the 
two countries next month. He expects the meeting to be 
beneficial to the arms deal as well. Deputy Minister Chaiyot 
says his ministry has invited the Thai Chamber of Commerce and 
the Federation of Thai Industries to consult on trade measures 
and cooperation with Italy on February 24. 

</TEXT>

