<F P=100> Thailand </F>
<H3> <TI>   Mongolian President on Official Visit 25-28 Feb </TI></H3>
<H4>   Prasong on President's Talks </H4>
<F P=102> BK2502140894 Bangkok Radio Thailand Network in Thai 1200 GMT 
25 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> BK2502140894 </F>
<F P=104>  Bangkok Radio Thailand Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Thai </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] This afternoon, the Mongolian president -- on an 
official visit to Thailand from 25-28 February as the guest of 
the government -- and his wife called on the prime minister at 
Government House. Speaking to reporters afterward, Foreign 
Minister Squadron Leader Prasong Sunsiri said this is the first 
visit to Thailand by such a high-ranking Mongolian official. He 
said there were broad discussions on political, economic, and 
social issues between the Thai and Mongolian leaders, who agreed 
that those issues have progressed well: 
  [Begin Prasong recording, in progress] ...called on our 
prime 
minister. They discussed political, economic, social, and trade 
issues. They agreed that Thai-Mongolian relations have 
proceeded well and will improve further. He asked us to 
consider Mongolia's wish to join ASEAN or APEC [Asia-Pacific 
Economic Cooperation] activities. The prime minister informed 
him that he has no objection in principle. Because those 
organizations include other countries, though, they will have to 
be consulted. On economic and trade issues, both sides agreed 
to increase the trade volume. Although the two countries are 
located far away from each other, communication between them is 
good. If the private sectors of both countries meet, there will 
be good prospects for greater trade. 
  Thailand offered scholarships for Mongolian students and 
invited Mongolian monks to study Buddhism in Thailand. A few 
Mongolian students and monks are already studying here. We 
offered several scholarships for Mongolian students, 
particularly in the field of public health. [end recording] 

</TEXT>

