<F P=100> South Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   Kim Yong-sam Holds 25 Feb News Conference </TI></H3>
<H4>   Officials Clarify Summit Proposal </H4>
<F P=102> SK2502112294 Seoul YONHAP in English 1110 GMT 25 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK2502112294 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul YONHAP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Seoul, Feb. 25 (YONHAP) -- President Kim Yong-sam's 
remarks on the promotion of an inter-Korean summit, made in his 
press conference on Friday, embodied the president's positive 
intent of resolving the nuclear question by all means, a ranking 
Chongwadae [presidential offices] official said. 
  Chong Chong-uk, senior presidential secretary for foreign 
affairs and national security, said President Kim meant to say 
he could promote a summit meeting if a summit is determined to 
be helpful to the resolution of nuclear and other inter-Korean 
issues. "We therefore expect that if and when the exchange of 
special envoys are realized, they would have talks so that the 
nuclear and other pending questions could be successfully taken 
up at a summit meeting," Chong said. 
  Another senior Chongwadae official said chances for the 
realization of a summit would depend on overall conditions such 
as the progress of U.S.-North Korea talks and the exchange of 
special envoys between the two sides of Korea. He stressed that 
President Kim's proposal for a summit does not run logically 
counter to the government's policy toward North Korea. "A 
summit was proposed with emphasis on the resolution of the 
nuclear question. But, once a summit meeting takes place, it 
could discuss overall issues pending between the two sides," he 
said. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

