<F P=100> South Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   Further on U.S.-DPRK Talks on Nuclear Issue </TI></H3>
<H4>   Sides Said To Reach Compromise </H4>
<F P=102> SK2402133794 Seoul KBS-1 Television Network in Korean 1233 
GMT 24 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> SK2402133794 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul KBS-1 Television Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Korean </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By Mun Chae-chol from Washington] </F>
  [Text] North Korea has agreed to resume the North-South 
dialogue at the same time nuclear inspections begin, and, as a 
result, it is expected that the North and South will be able to 
exchange special envoys soon. 
  In the working-level contact which continued for the second 
day in New York this morning, Korean time, the United States and 
North Korea reportedly have virtually finished drafting the 
letter of agreement which contains the four principles: The 
International Atomic Energy Agency will start nuclear 
inspections on 1 March; at the same time, the discontinuation of 
the Team Spirit exercise for this year will be announced; 
North-South dialogue for the exchange of special envoys will 
start; and the third round of U.S.-North Korea high-level talks 
will resume next month. 
  In drafting the agreement, the United States and North Korea 
had different views on the timing of the North-South exchange of 
special envoys and on the third round of U.S.-North Korea 
high-level talks. However, North Korea agreed that it would 
affirmatively examine the North-South contact for the exchange 
of special envoys in case South Korea so proposes. As a result, 
a compromise was reached. 
  The United States agreed that the third round of U.S.-North 
Korea high-level talks would be held late March on the condition 
that North Korea resumes the North-South dialogue. 
  If North Korea obtains approval for the agreement with the 
United States from the Pyongyang authorities, the sides are 
expected to exchange the final letter of agreement at the 
third-day working-level contact which will open late this 
evening Korean time. However, Washington and New York sources 
have said that the sides would not release a joint communique 
because their meeting is a working-level contact. 

</TEXT>

