<F P=100> NORTHEAST ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Kubota Cites Ways To Shift Trade Balance </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW2502040294 Tokyo KYODO in English 0333 GMT 25 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2502040294 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, Feb. 25 KYODO -- Japan's economic planning 
chief called for effective use of both macroeconomic and 
microeconomic measures Friday [25 February] as a way to reduce 
the nation's huge current account surplus. The large Japanese 
surplus is not "satisfactory" for the global economy, Manae 
Kubota, director general of the Economic Planning Agency [EPA], 
told a regular press conference. 
  As one of the macroeconomic measures, the EPA will hammer 
out 
ways to shift huge individual savings in Japan to housing 
investment and social infrastructure, Kubota said. 
  The booming housing sector has a great potential for further 
demand, she said. 
  Quicker improvement regarding the current account balance 
could come with deregulation and other microeconomic policies 
that have "sharper" effects on a short-term basis, she said. 
  Kubota cited import promotion and government procurement as 
possible microeconomic areas in which the government could take 
more action. She said the EPA will include these macro and 
microeconomic measures in a market-opening package to be 
unveiled by the government by the end of March. 
  Kubota reiterated that the 2.8 percent forecast by the 
government as the ratio of the current account surplus against 
gross domestic product (GDP) in fiscal 1994, starting April 1, 
is not a target but is only a reference figure. Such an area is 
not within government control, she said, noting that a country's 
trade balance is affected by external factors such as the 
international situation and economic activities of foreign 
countries. 
  She said Japan's current account balance figures have failed 
to meet original government projections in most years since 
fiscal 1955. 
  Kubota called for effective use of her agency's trade 
ombudsman system in monitoring Japan's trade balance changes. 
The office of trade and investment ombudsman was inaugurated 
Friday as a way to gauge the openness of Japan's markets. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

