<F P=100> NORTHEAST ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Reportage on Market-Opening Issue Continues </TI></H3>
<H4>   Takemura on Liberalization Timing </H4>
<F P=102> OW2502024194 Tokyo KYODO in English 0223 GMT 25 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2502024194 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, Feb. 25 KYODO -- Prime Minister Morihiro 
Hosokawa wants measures on further liberalizing the Japanese 
market to be decided by the end of March, Chief Cabinet 
Secretary Masayoshi Takemura told reporters Friday [25 February]. 
  Cabinet ministers, including Foreign Minister Tsutomu Hata 
and International Trade and Industry Minister Hiroshi Kumagai, 
gathered at Hosokawa's official residence Friday to start 
determining the specifics of an earlier-announced government 
plan to open up the domestic market. 
  Aimed at overcoming the deadlock in Japan-U.S. "framework" 
trade talks, the plan includes encouraging imports and 
investment, lifting regulations, facilitating the procedures 
involved in government orders and spurring competitive policies. 
The government hopes the measures will help allay criticism 
mounting in the United States over Japan's huge trade surplus, 
and stave off the possibility of U.S. retaliatory measures. 
  The Japanese officials started discussions on the 
government's policy to introduce liberalizing measures for the 
automobile, auto parts and insurance markets -- three areas in 
which Japan spurned U.S. requests to set "numerical import 
targets." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

