<F P=100> NORTHEAST ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Reportage on Market-Opening Issue Continues </TI></H3>
<H4>   Cabinet Meeting Discusses Measures </H4>
<F P=102> OW2502041594 Tokyo KYODO in English 0331 GMT 25 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2502041594 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, Feb. 25 KYODO -- Japan will formulate a set 
of fresh measures to open its markets further to foreign 
competition by the end of March, Chief Cabinet Secretary 
Masayoshi Takemura said Friday [25 February]. 
  The decision emerged at a meeting of related cabinet 
ministers held at prime minister Morihiro hosokawa's official 
residence. 
  The top government spokesman quoted the premier as telling 
the meeting that it is natural for Japan to take necessary 
market- opening steps on its own volition, regardless of its 
trade negotiations with the United States. 
  Takemura told a news conference the planned government 
package will not only cover four areas pinpointed earlier but 
will also include other necessary measures to further open 
Japan's markets. 
  The government said last week it will map out a program to 
speed up deregulation, strengthen import and investment 
promotion steps, revamp competition policy and improve 
government procurement processes. 
  Friday's meeting brought together Hosokawa, Takemura and 
chiefs of the foreign, finance, trade, posts, health and 
transport ministries, as well as those of the Economic Planning 
Agency and of the Management and Coordination Agency. 
  The schedule of the next such cabinet meeting is not yet 
fixed, Takemura said. 
  The cabinet meeting came as the U.S. is increasing pressure 
on Japan to slash its huge trade surplus following the collapse 
of bilateral trade talks. 
  On February 11, Hosokawa and U.S. President Bill Clinton 
failed to strike a deal on ways to cut Japan's trade surplus 
with the U.S. Tokyo spurned a demand from Washington to set 
numerical targets to gauge the openness of its markets to 
imports. 
  Asked if Japan will maintain its position of refusing 
numerical targets in working out a fresh market-opening package, 
Takemura said, "of course, that's our basic stance." 
  He said no ministers referred in their meeting to an idea of 
setting nonbinding targets for measuring progress in opening 
Japan's markets. 
  Takemura also said they did not discuss a proposed dispatch 
of a special envoy to the U.S. to break the deadlock over trade. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

