<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Lack of Translators Limits Siberia Air Traffic </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW2502120794 Tokyo KYODO in English 1148 GMT 25 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2502120794 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, Feb. 25 KYODO -- Commericial air traffic 
over Siberia is being limited by the need for translators by 
officials in Khabarovsk to communicate with airline pilots, 
officials said Friday [25 February] at the close of talks aimed 
at relaxing restrictions in Russian airspace. 
  Russian officials attending the four-day talks explained 
that 
to ensure the safety of flights over Siberia it is necessary to 
limit the number to six per hour, even though new facilities 
have been built to enhance the reliability of communications 
equipment. 
  The Russian officials suggested that a parallel route could 
be established over Siberia that would allow nine filghts an 
hour, but Japan said the proposal would require building new 
radar facilities. 
  However, Japan said it would consider the proposal. The two 
countries will meet again in mid-March. 
  A Japanese Transport Ministry official said Friday that 
officials were unaware that translators were being used. They 
stressed that the need for improved traffic control in the 
Siberian route will increase with the opening of the Kansai 
International Airport in September. 
  Russia, citing the diminished reliability of its 
communication facilities, has been restricting the number of 
commercial flights over Siberia since December to six per hour, 
only a third of the previous volume of traffic. 
  The restriction initially caused delays of as much as two 
and 
a half hours for flights in and out of Narita Airport, and even 
though the situation has improved since then, flight delays of 
30 to 40 minutes are still common, officials said. 
  The Siberian route is the main air route linking Japan and 
Europe, used daily by some 40 to 50 airliners both into and out 
of Tokyo. 

</TEXT>

