<H3> <TI>   Peruvian Official on Desire To Join APEC </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW2502131594 Tokyo KYODO in English 1235 GMT 25 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2502131594 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, Feb. 25 KYODO -- Peru's prime minister and 
Mongolia's president separately said Friday [25 February] their 
countries want to become members of the Asia-Pacific Economic 
Cooperation (APEC) forum. 
  In Tokyo, Peruvian Prime Minister Efrain Goldenberg, who is 
concurrently foreign minister, asked Japanese Foreign Minister 
Tsutomu Hata for support in Lima's bid to participate in APEC, 
Foreign Ministry officials said. 
  Hata responded positively, saying he hopes to relay to 
related nations Peru's desire to take part in the regional 
economic group, they said. 
  Hata was quoted as saying the Peruvian Government led by 
President Alberto Fujimori has promoted democratization and is 
making efforts to resolve difficulties. 
  Goldenberg, visiting Japan to attend a seminar, conveyed a 
message by Fujimori that he is willing to invite Hata to his 
country, the officials said. 
  In Bangkok, Mongolian President Punsalmaagiyn Ochirbat met 
Thai Premier Chuan Likphai and said Mongolia hopes to join APEC 
and have close relations with the Association of Southeast Asian 
Nations (ASEAN), Thai officials said. 
  Ochirbat is scheduled to visit Laos and Vietnam following 
Thailand. 

</TEXT>

