<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   JISF: Steel Exports for 1993 Rise 23.8 Percent </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW2402090994 Tokyo KYODO in English 0852 GMT 24 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2402090994 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, Feb. 24 KYODO -- Japan's steel exports in 
1993 rose 23.8 percent from 1992 to 23,506,000 tons, exceeding 
20 million tons for the first time in four years, an industry 
group said Thursday [24 February]. The Japan Iron and Steel 
Federation [JISF] said the exports, on a shipment basis, also 
posted the third consecutive year-on-year rise. 
  It attributed the sharp export growth to increased exports 
early in the year to China, whose economy is sharply expanding. 
  The dollar value of the exports rose 9.3 percent, but the 
yen 
value dropped 4.1 percent, due to the yen's appreciation against 
the dollar, the federation said. 
  The unit price of all exports dropped to 73,400 yen per ton, 
down 21,400 yen from the previous year. It was the lowest 
average unit price in six years. 
  Despite an increase in export volume, export earnings showed 
little growth, industry officials said, predicting exports in 
1994 will level off from 1993 both in volume and value. 
  The federation also reported exports to China increased 
2.9-fold to 6,910,000 tons. 
  Shipments to Taiwan rose 19.0 percent to 2,910,000 tons and 
those to South Korea increased 1.5 percent to 1,670,000 tons. 
But exports to the United States plunged 30.6 percent to 
1,820,000 tons. 
  Steel imports in 1993 increased 3.6 percent to 9,185,000 
tons, the federation said. 

</TEXT>

