<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Ministry To Raise Postal Insurance Premiums </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW2502114894 Tokyo KYODO in English 1103 GMT 25 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2502114894 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, Feb. 25 KYODO -- The Postal Ministry said 
Friday [25 February] it will raise postal insurance premiums by 
an average 10.3 percent, effective April 1. 
  The Ministry of Posts and Telecommunications said a ministry 
advisory panel, the Postal Services Council, approved on Friday 
the first premium increase in 46 years for new postal insurance 
policies. 
  The raise is necessitated by a fall in interest rates, which 
has cut the estimated yield on investments of insurance funds, 
ministry officials said. 
  They said the premiums will be increased by 9.7 percent for 
ordinary postal insurance and by 17.3 percent for annuity 
insurance. 
  Under the plan, the monthly premium payment for a 10-year 
savings-type endowment insurance, which pays 1 million yen for 
death or at maturity, will be hiked to 7,940 yen for a 
40-year-old male, up 8.3 percent. 
  The monthly payment for life annuity contracts, which start 
pension payments at age 60, will be raised to 34,722 yen for a 
50- year-old female, up 37.6 percent. 
  The estimated yield on investments of postal insurance funds 
in fiscal 1993, ending next March 31, has fallen to about 5 
percent from 5.8 percent the previous year and is likely to drop 
to a range of 4 to 5 percent in fiscal 1994, the officials said. 

</TEXT>

