<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Foreign Ministry Suspends Debate on EAEC Role </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW2402203894 Tokyo TOKYO SHIMBUN in Japanese 23 Feb 94 
Morning Edition p 2 -- FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> OW2402203894 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo TOKYO SHIMBUN </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Japanese </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] On 22 February, a Foreign Ministry source disclosed 
that the ministry has made firm its decision to tentatively put 
a freeze on internal debates over whether it would be proper for 
Japan to participate in the East Asia Economic Caucus (EAEC). 
  The Foreign Ministry has made this decision in consideration 
of Japan's relations with the United States, which is strongly 
opposed to the establishment of the EAEC. Circumstances are 
such that even if debates on this issue are resumed in the 
future, it cannot be predicted whether Japan will decide to 
participate in the organization. Thus, Japan's currently 
strained relations with the United States are affecting its 
Asian policy, too. 
  The EAEC plan is aimed at unifying nations in the East Asian 
region. It has its origins in the East Asia Economic Group 
(EAEG) plan proposed by Malaysian Prime Minister Mohamed 
Mahathir. The United States is strongly opposed to the plan 
because it excludes such nations as the United States, Canada, 
Australia, and New Zealand. 

</TEXT>

