<F P=100> Brunei, Malaysia &amp; Singapore </F>
<F P=101> Malaysia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Air Force Chief: Need More Hawk Fighter Planes </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  BK2502090394 Kuala Lumpur Voice of Malaysia in English 0600 
GMT 25 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> BK2502090394 </F>
<F P=104>  Kuala Lumpur Voice of Malaysia </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Air Force Chief Lieutenant General Datuk Abdul Gani 
Aziz says Malaysia needs more Hawk 200 jet fighters to 
strengthen its air defense. He is of the view that the 20 Hawk 
aircraft being acquired to replace the A-4 Skyhawk are 
insufficient. The Air Force plans to increase the number of 
Hawk aircraft in the future. He told reporters this at the RMAF 
[Royal Malaysian Air Force] base in Butterworth. Earlier, Datuk 
Abdul Gani was present at the handing-over of a Hawk 100, one of 
the two aircraft acquired from Britain for the purpose of 
training. The purchase of the 20 Hawk was made under a 
memorandum of understanding signed by the Malaysian and British 
Governments three years ago. 

</TEXT>

