<F P=100> SLOVENIA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Zhirinovskiy on Private Visit to Ljubljana </TI></H3>
<H4>   Threatens Russian UN Withdrawal </H4>
<F P=102> LD2801222294 Belgrade TANJUG in English 2134 GMT 28 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2801222294 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> ["Pool" item] </F>
  [Text] Ljubljana, Jan 28 (TANJUG) -- Russia's Liberal 
Democratic Party leader Vladimir Zhirinovskiy said on Friday 
that if the United Nations decided to mount air attacks on 
Bosnian Serbs he would move in parliament for Russia's 
withdrawal from the U.N. which, he said, would be the end of the 
world organization. Speaking at a press conference in Ljubljana 
where he arrived on Thursday [27 January] on a short private 
visit, Zhirinovskiy resolutely opposed any military action in 
former Yugoslavia. Any further foreign involvement in the 
Yugoslav crisis, especially in war-torn Bosnia-Herzegovina, 
would inevitably trigger world war three, he argued. 
  The first precondition for resolving the crisis in the 
Balkans is to withdraw foreign troops from the territory of 
former Yugoslavia. Otherwise, the conflict would continue for 
another 20 or 30 years, said Zhirinovskiy. 
  At the press conference attended by over 100 reporters from 
Europe, Japan and the United States, Zhirinovskiy said he would 
present his plan for resolving the Bosnia crisis during his 
visit to Belgrade on Sunday. TANJUG learns unofficially that 
Zhirinovskiy will be visiting Belgrade at the invitation of the 
Russian-Serbian Friendship Society. 
  In Slovenia, Zhirinovskiy was highly criticial of the 
disintegration of the Slavic states into a host of 
city-statelettes. If this trend continues, the entire world 
will break up because the retailoring of borders in one case 
will encourage the same practice in another. Slovenia violently 
seceded from the former Yugoslav Federation in 1991. 
  Asked whether he had his own ideas for the formation of a 
new 
Yugoslav community, Zhirinovskiy said a confederation of 
Slovenes, Serbs and Croats could not be ruled out. 

</TEXT>

