<H3> <TI>   Zhirinovskiy on Private Visit to Ljubljana </TI></H3>
<H4>   Leaves Slovenia for Belgrade </H4>
<F P=102> LD3001125394 Belgrade TANJUG Domestic Service in 
Serbo-Croatian 1153 GMT 30 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD3001125394 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG Domestic Service </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Serbo-Croatian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Ljubljana, 30 Jan (TANJUG) -- Vladimir Zhirinovskiy, 
president of the Russian Liberal Democratic Party, left Slovenia 
for Budapest this morning. He will continue his journey to 
Belgrade this afternoon. 
  "I would like to show the Serbs that there exists another 
Russia, a new leading political party, a new Russian 
parliament", said Zhirinovskiy in his statement for TANJUG. 
  He hinted at "Russia taking a new stand in order that the 
war 
in former Bosnia-Herzegovina may end as soon as possible", and 
so that "no Serb and no Slav would ever have to die in the 
Balkans. The Balkans will flourish" -- was the message of the 
leader of the Russian Liberal Democrats. 
  In the course of his official and unofficial meetings in 
Serbia and the Serb Republic [in Bosnia-Herzegovina], 
Zhirinovskiy is expected to put forward his proposals for the 
settlement of the Yugoslav crisis, and especially for an end to 
the war in former Bosnia-Herzegovina. Fully supporting the 
Serbian and Montenegrin people, whom he considers as brotherly, 
he will strongly oppose the air strikes on Bosnian Serbs 
persistently threatened by the United Nations and NATO. 
  "My party and the official Russian policy will keep 
demanding 
that the international community abolish the sanctions against 
the FRY and allow its return back among the recognized European 
countries", said Zhirinovskiy. 

</TEXT>

