<F P=100> SLOVENIA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Government Considering Normalizing FRY Ties </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD3101200194 Belgrade TANJUG in English 1900 GMT 31 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD3101200194 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Ljubljana, Jan 31 (TANJUG) -- Slovenia is 
considering a normalisation of the relations with the Federal 
Republic of Yugoslavia (F.R.Y.), Slovenian Foreign Minister 
Lojze Peterle said on Monday [31 January]. At a press 
conference in Ljubljana Peterle underscored Slovenia's official 
stand that the normalisation of the relations with the F.R.Y. 
was of interest for this former member of the Yugoslav 
Federation, especially after the increasingly successful 
contacts between Belgrade and Zagreb. The Slovenian Foreign 
Ministry has been actively monitoring all recent changes in the 
Ljubljana-Belgrade relations, said Peterle but did not elaborate. 
  Slovenia's Foreign Ministry is studying what should be done 
for the setting up of the contacts between Ljubljana and 
Belgrade, said the minister and added that proposals would be 
submitted to the Slovenian Government in order to examine them 
at one of its next sessions. The F.R.Y. recognized Slovenia in 
late summer of 1992, as part of the preparations for the London 
Conference on resolving the Yugoslav crisis. At that time, 
Slovenia did not show any interest in the normalisation of the 
relations with the F.R.Y. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-30254 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "dreeu021_k_94003" </HT>


