<F P=100> CROATIA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Commentary Views U.S. Senate Resolution </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU3101160794 Zagreb VJESNIK in Serbo-Croatian 29 Jan 94 p 1 </F>
<F P=103> AU3101160794 </F>
<F P=104>  Zagreb VJESNIK </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Serbo-Croatian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Commentary by Aleksandar Milosevic: "Lost Sheep"] </F>
  [Text] Although nonbinding, the resolution of the U.S. 
Senate demanding the lifting of the arms embargo against the 
Bosnian Muslims is more than telling. First of all it reveals 
the prevalent way of thinking in this leading U.S. institution 
regarding the solution to the Bosnia-Herzegovina conflict. The 
U.S. Senate obviously believes that a political solution is 
impossible, and so the military solution imposes itself. 
Additionally, this resolution confirms that -- out of narrow 
internal interests -- the United States wants to radicalize its 
behavior in order to appease its allies in the Islamic and Arab 
world. 
  Both these facts, however, show that there is a large rift 
in 
interests and intentions between Europe and the United States 
when it comes to solving the crisis on the territory of the 
former Yugoslavia. While the European Union, divided over the 
national interests of France, Great Britain, and Germany -- and 
in the shadow of Russian diplomatic moves -- is trying in vain 
to find a common denominator for its policy, the United States 
is trying to move things with loud threats of air strikes and 
now of lifting the arms embargo against Alija Izetbegovic's 
army. However, it is hard to believe that the real way will be 
found with such diversified interests. The European West and 
the United States still resemble lost sheep far more than a 
respectable political force. 
  Although one should not, in principle, draw parallels with 
the past for day to day political events, one should 
nevertheless say that the U.S. Senate did not pass such a 
resolution, or indeed any resolution, binding or otherwise, when 
Croatia was the victim of the Serbian aggression. Besides, the 
arms that Alija Izetbegovic would get with the lifting of the 
embargo would, at least initially, be used exclusively against 
the Croats in central Bosnia and the Neretva River valley. That 
is why Croatia cannot remain calm and unconcerned in the face of 
the latest resolution of the U.S. Senate. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-30258 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "dreeu021_c_94001" </HT>


