<F P=100> BOSNIA-HERZEGOVINA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Karadzic Expects Conflict To Be Settled `by War' </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU0102135894 Paris AFP in English 1334 GMT 1 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU0102135894 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Belgrade, Feb 1 (AFP) -- Bosnian Serb leader Radovan 
Karadzic said he expected the Bosnian conflict to be settled by 
war, in a statement Tuesday [1 February] to the Bosnian Serb 
news agency SRNA. 
  "The international community is going to allow the conflict 
to be settled by war, which means that the world will give 
Moslems credit for land acquired through fighting. This same 
principle should be adopted for the Serbs," he said. 
  The military headquarters for the self-proclaimed Serb 
republic of Bosnia on Monday decided to mobilize "everyone able 
to be mobilized, including women," in order to "end the war as 
quickly as possible." 
  A reorganization of the army, as well as the introduction of 
"stricter measures regarding deserters" were decided by the 
chief of staff of the Bosnian Serb army. 
  Karadzic, quoted by SRNA, said Bosnian Serbs' military goals 
were to "modernize its army, increase its efficiency, ensure the 
defense of our republic and vanquish our enemies." 
  This required "the entire nation to mobilize for work or 
war," he said. 
  Bosnian Serb military commanders have repeatedly charged 
that 
the Moslem-majority Bosnian Government Army is preparing a 
large-scale offensive for the spring. 
  The Bosnian Serb leader also repeated his opposition to 
reopening the airport at Tuzla, the Moslem-controlled city in 
northeastern Bosnia. "Any reopening of Tuzla airport is not 
motivated by humanitarian reasons but by military reasons," he 
said. 
  The stage for more fighting was set after the last attempt 
to 
negotiate a settlement to the Bosnian conflict, two days of 
talks by the warring parties in Geneva last month, failed to 
make any progress. European Community negotiator David Owen at 
the time said the sides appeared to be gearing for new 
offensives after the winter, after 21 months of war. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-30272 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "dreeu021_i_94003" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-EEU-94-021 </AU>
Document Type:Daily Report 
<DATE1>  1 Feb 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> BOSNIA-HERZEGOVINA </F>
<H3> <TI>   U.S. Accused of Supplying Arms to Muslims </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2801183894 Belgrade TANJUG Domestic Service in 
Serbo-Croatian 1656 GMT 28 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2801183894 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG Domestic Service </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Serbo-Croatian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Jagodina, 28 Jan (TANJUG) -- Radovan Karadzic, 
president of the Srpska republic, said today that international 
power brokers were doing as they pleased and were playing cruel 
games with the nerves of an entire nation that wants only what 
belongs to it. 
  Commenting for Radio Jagodina [in Serbia] on the latest 
threats of military intervention and proposals to lift the arms 
embargo for the Muslim side only, Karadzic said that the Bosnian 
Serbs have done everything for a peaceful solution but they were 
still exposed to relentless threats. 
  In reality, Srebrenica has never been a problem because we 
have allowed the Dutch battalion to replace the Canadian unit. 
However, the international community needs to aggravate the 
situation due to its obligations to the Islamic states. France 
wants to humiliate the NATO alliance and cause its downfall and 
so forth, Karadzic said. 
  Karadzic said once again that the opening of Tuzla airport 
was out of the question because this would mean that the Muslims 
would receive large amounts of weapons, which they were getting 
anyway. 
  It is absurd to discuss the lifting of the embargo on 
weapons 
for the Muslims when they have been receiving them from the 
Americans and Islamic states for a long time. The Muslims are 
well armed and, according to their own claims, they have 200,000 
soldiers. We think that they have even more, Karadzic said. 
  He also spoke of the discrepancy between Europe and the 
United States in respect of the ways for solving the Bosnian 
crisis and about the increasing number of claims by certain 
states that negotiations were no longer necessary as the Muslims 
were scoring victories on the battlefield. 
  The Serbs could be interested in this option. If we are 
talking about a status quo, the Serbs will keep 70 percent of 
the territory of former Bosnia-Herzegovina or possibly go down 
to 64 percent to which we have the right in the name of peace. 
If the Muslims opt for war, all percentages will be out of the 
question, Karadzic said. 
  Karadzic said that the option chosen by the Muslims and 
their 
allies was already clear, adding that this would perhaps finally 
be revealed as early as the next round of Geneva negotiations 
scheduled for 10 February. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-30273 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "dreeu021_i_94004" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-EEU-94-021 </AU>
Document Type:Daily Report 
<DATE1>  1 Feb 1994 </DATE1>

