<F P=100> BOSNIA-HERZEGOVINA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Muslims `Fiercely Fighting' With Croats, Serbs </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD3101191294 Belgrade TANJUG in English 1602 GMT 31 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD3101191294 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> ["Pool" item] </F>
  [Text] Belgrade, Jan 31 (TANJUG) -- Bosnian Moslems and 
Croats have been fiercely fighting over the past 24 hours in 
nearly all disputed territories, and Moslems have also continued 
attacks and provocations against the Serbs, Bosnian Serb 
military sources announced Monday. 
  Moslem Radio Sarajevo reports that three civilians have been 
killed and 14 wounded when the forces of Bosnian Croats and of 
the former Yugoslav Republic of Croatia Sunday afternoon fired 
over 80 artillery shells on the Moslem part of Mostar, town in 
the southern part of the former Yugoslav Republic of 
Bosnia-Herzegovina. 
  According to Moslem media, the Croat anti-aricraft and 
artillery units Sunday night fired on demarcation lines in 
Mostar, and Monday morning renewed their attacks on Moslem 
positions in Konjic, Jablanica and Prozor areas in central 
Bosnia. 
  Bosnian Serb military sources report that Moslem forces have 
been attacking practically all Serb communities and defense 
lines in the Sarajevo area, trying unsuccessfully to provoke 
large-scale clashes in order to renew the anti-Serb media 
campaign. 
  According to the same sources, Moslem forces have also 
attacked Serb communities and positions in northern 
Bosnia-Herzegovina -- the areas of Doboj, Gradacac and Maglaj, 
as well as Olovo in central Bosnia. 
  Moslem formations have carried out a fierce artillery and 
infantry attack on Serb positions in the Maglaj area, but have 
had to withdraw, with losses, to their starting point, Bosnian 
Serb military sources report. 

</TEXT>

