<H3> <TI>   Baudys on Arrest of UNPROFOR Troops </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU2701172294 Prague CTK in English 1613 GMT 27 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU2701172294 </F>
<F P=104>  Prague CTK </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Prague, Jan 27 (CTK) -- Defense Minister Antonin 
Baudys confirmed to CTK today that three Czech UNPROFOR [United 
Nations Protection Forces] soldiers arrested on the 
Austrian-Czech border Wednesday [26 January] for alleged weapons 
smuggling were not carrying six hand grenades or any explosives, 
as had been reported. 
  What they were carrying, Baudys said, was one (functional) 
trophy pistol and a fake grenade with no fuse or charge. The 
soldiers were travelling with their unit by bus back to the 
Czech Republic for their regular leave when a 60-man Austrian 
anti-terrorist commando group stopped the unit's two buses at 
the Wullovitz-Dolni Dvoriste border crossing, removed the three 
soldiers, questioned them, and handed them several hours later 
to Czech authorities in Dolni Dvoriste. The other 67 soldiers 
cleared customs with no problem. 
  Baudys said the raid had apparently been intended to 
intercept someone else and probably been prepared in advance, 
since accompanying the commandos were Austrian journalists and 
TV crews. 
  He admitted that the three soldiers had committed an 
offence, 
"but it doesn't deserve the dramatic antics of the whole 
situation and with which it was carried by the media." 
  The three are now in Cesky Krumlov, south Bohemia -- where 
Czech UNPROFOR troops are trained -- awaiting a decision by 
military police and state representatives on their fate. 
  On Wednesday an Austrian rapid deployment team stopped 
another bus of Czech UNPROFOR soldiers heading for Vienna. 
According to the AUSTRIAN PRESS AGENCY (APA), they found a 
handgun, two clips and 40 rounds of ammunition for a Kalashnikov 
machine gun. 
  According to Jaromir Novotny, director of the Czech Defence 
Ministry's Foreign Affairs Section, no soldiers were questioned 
and the bus was allowed to reach the Czech Republic. He could 
not confirm the discovery of the weapons as he had not received 
an official Austrian report, he said. 

</TEXT>

