<F P=101> Czech Republic </F>
<H3> <TI>   Foreign Trade Increased 10.6 Percent in 1993 </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU3101161294 Prague CTK in English 1540 GMT 31 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU3101161294 </F>
<F P=104>  Prague CTK </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Prague Jan 31 (CTK) -- The Czech Republic's foreign 
trade turnover was 10.6 percent higher in 1993 than it was in 
1992, according to the preliminary results of a Czech Statistics 
Office (CSU) study. 
  Czech imports increased by 2.7 percent and exports by 20.0 
percent last year. The only countries with whom Czech trade 
decreased were those of the former Soviet Union. Czech Republic 
exports and imports increased to all other countries. 
  A total of 58.0 percent of Czech trade in 1993 was made with 
countries with mature market economies, while 8.7 percent was 
exchanged with former members of the Soviet Union and 6.1 
percent with other Eastern European states in economic 
transformation. 
  The Czech Republic's trade surplus was 5.9 billion crowns 
($200 million) last year. The largest surplus was recorded with 
developing countries (13.6 billion crowns, $453 million), while 
the surplus with European Union states was 7.5 billion crowns 
($250 million). The Czech Republic's largest trade deficit was 
with countries of the former Soviet Union ($19.8 billion, $660 
million). 
  Czech trade with Slovakia was at a surplus balance of 9.6 
billion crowns ($320 million). 

</TEXT>

