<H3> <TI>   Defense Minister Cited on TV Frequency Debate </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2701223094 Warsaw PAP in English 2136 GMT 27 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2701223094 </F>
<F P=104>  Warsaw PAP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Warsaw, Jan 27 -- Minister of Defence Piotr 
Kolodziejdzyk has declared he wants to put an end to the "war 
over frequencies" waged by his ministry with the National Radio 
and Television Council (KRRIT), according to parliamentary 
Deputy Marek Siwiec, a member of the council. 
  Siwiec was speaking to reporters on Thursday following a 
meeting with Kolodziejdzyk. The meeting had been arranged after 
Siwiec had submitted a formal question in parliament. However, 
Siwiec added that he was still waiting for a formal reply from 
the minister. 
  The minister informed Siwiec about the measures to be taken 
by the Armed Forces in order to hand over to civilian users a 
number of frequencies used by the Air Force telecommunications 
services. However, according to Siwiec, Kolodziejdzyk had argued 
that the problem could be successfuly overcome only on condition 
that the Army received an extra 2 trillion zlotys (ca. 90 m 
dollars) to finance necessary technical restructuring. 

</TEXT>

