<F P=100> BULGARIA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Iranian Foreign Minister Arrives for Visit </TI></H3>
<H4>   Daskalov Backs Expansion of Ties </H4>
<F P=102> LD0102134494 Tehran IRNA in English 1144 GMT 1 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0102134494 </F>
<F P=104>  Tehran IRNA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Sofia, Feb. 1, IRNA-- Bulgarian Foreign Minister 
Stanislav Daskalov Monday called for promotion of Tehran-Sofia 
ties. 
  Speaking to IRNA, Daskalov termed his first round of talks 
with the visiting Iranian Foreign Minister 'Ali Akbar Velayati 
as constructive and said Sofia was ready to sign trade agreement 
with Tehran. He said that the two countries have agreed to set 
up a joint commission for cultural cooperation. 
  Daskalov stressed that his country would not allow its 
relations with Iran be influenced by pressure of foreign powers. 
He said that differences of views existed between the two 
countries with regards to settling the Bosnian crisis but added 
that this cannot hamper expansion of Tehran-Sofia relations. 
He said his country favoured lifting sanctions on former 
Yugoslavia adding that Iran has a different approach to the 
issue. He added that the U.S., Russia and the U.N. play a key 
role in settling the Bosnian crisis. 
  Daskalov declined to give an explicit comment to the 
question 
on why Europe and the U.S. did not put an end to the Bosnian 
tragedy. 

</TEXT>

