<F P=100> YUGOSLAVIA </F>
<F P=101> Macedonia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Ex-PDP Official Arrested for Arms Smuggling </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU0202110294 Skopje MIC in English 1 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU0202110294 </F>
<F P=104>  Skopje MIC </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Unattributed report: "Mithat Emini Arrested"] </F>
  [Text] The former secretary-general of PDP [Party for 
Democratic Prosperity] was arrested on Saturday [29 January] 
under the charges of founded suspicion that he was involved in 
the affair with the organization of paramilitary Albanian 
formations in Macedonia and arms smuggling, MIC reports, quoting 
reliable sources in the interior ministry. The district 
attorney Gligor Serafimovski confirmed this information to MIC. 
However, he denied that Emini was transferred from prison in 
Skopje to the state polyclinic, due to heart difficulties. MIC 
found out that the court proceedings of the group of Albanians, 
including an Albanian with Macedonian and US citizenship, all 
indicted under the same charges, are expected to begin toward 
the end of this week. 
  Toward the beginning of last November, the Macedonian police 
arrested the Deputy Minister of Defense Husein Haskaj, together 
with a larger group of Albanians, under the suspicion of 
smuggling arms and organizing paramilitary and parapolice 
organizations in Macedonia. The Minister of the Interior 
Ljubomir Frckovski stated, at the time, that "there is a founded 
suspicion that the Deputy Minister of Defense Haskaj was 
involved in the expert estimation and giving advice to a foreign 
state, which is in the sphere of giving out state secrets." The 
Ministry of Defense denied this information and explained that 
Haskaj did not have at his disposal information about the 
defense plan of the Republic of Macedonia. Frckovski also 
denied that an arsenal of 300 automatic guns were found on the 
suspects, but only 35. Frckovski also denied that a list of 
20,000 recruits of the Albanian paramilitary in Macedonia was 
also found on the people arrested. "It is quite possible," 
Frckovski said, "that the arrested individuals were preparing a 
concept for organized paramilitary action." 
  The police then announced that this was otherwise the fourth 
cut off arms smuggling channel in Macedonia. The first had come 
from Croatia through Bulgaria, the second from FRY through 
Bulgaria, and third through Salonika, into Macedonia. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-30339 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "dreeu022_y_94007" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-EEU-94-022 </AU>
Document Type:Daily Report 
<DATE1>  2 Feb 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> YUGOSLAVIA </F>
<F P=101> Macedonia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Deputies `Fear' Albanian Census Count </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU0202105894 Tirana TVSH Television Network in Albanian 1900 
GMT 1 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> AU0202105894 </F>
<F P=104>  Tirana TVSH Television Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Albanian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Let us listen to a report from Ibajete Hajrullahu 
about the problems within the Party for Democratic Prosperity 
[PDP] in Macedonia and the suspension of the Macedonian 
parliament session, scheduled to discuss the census bill: 
  [Hajrullahu] After many efforts to reach an agreement 
between the two factions in the PDP, this was attained in the 
meeting held in Tetove. On this occasion, a joint council made 
up of representatives from both former councils was formed to 
make preparations for the early congress. The council also 
comprised one representative from every PDP branch. 
  This council will hold its first meeting on 3 February at 
the 
PDP headquarters in Tetove. Meanwhile, the Macedonian Assembly 
continued its suspended proceedings regarding the government's 
proposal to discuss the census law. The discussions by 
Macedonian deputies displayed the fear that by conducting an 
objective census, the number of Albanians will turn out to be 
greater than the present one, which the Macedonians used to 
manipulate. However, in drafting the law the government's main 
aim is not that it should be acceptable for Albanians as well. 
The Albanian deputies again presented their remarks requesting 
no more than a real and objective census and the return of lost 
belief in the Republic's Statistics Department. The debate was 
again suspended. 

</TEXT>

