<F P=100> BOSNIA-HERZEGOVINA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Karadzic, Akashi Cited on Tuzla Airport </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU0102204794 Belgrade RTB Television Network in 
Serbo-Croatian 1830 GMT 1 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> AU0102204794 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade RTB Television Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Serbo-Croatian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] After visiting several cities in the former 
Yugoslavia, including Sarajevo, Yasushi Akashi, special envoy of 
the UN secretary general, and head of the UN Protection Forces 
[UNPROFOR] in the former Yugoslavia, held talks today in 
Belgrade with Dr. Radovan Karadzic, president of the Srpska 
republic. They discussed all the issues that are currently 
complicating the situation in the former Bosnia-Herzegovina [as 
heard], particularly certain demands by the international 
community issued to the leadership of the Srpska republic. 
  [Begin recording] [Akashi, in English with superimposed 
Serbo-Croatian translation] There should be no difficulties 
concerning the rotation of the UNPROFOR troops in Srebrenica, 
and I hope that this rotation, based on this agreement, will be 
completed by the end of February. 
  As for the opening of Tuzla airport, I believe that Dr. 
Karadzic is keeping an open mind. He wants to explore our 
suggestions. He has to consult his assembly, but we are ready 
to take into account his concerns regarding the security and 
other aspects of this. 
  We have a clear mandate from the UN secretary general to 
open 
the airport by peaceful means, by negotiations, but if that is 
not successful, then there is the possibility of the use of a 
minimum of force for self-defense. However, I am sure that we 
agree that we will do everything possible to avoid that kind of 
an escalation. 
  [Unidentified correspondent] How do you understand the 
latest 
mandate that you have been given by Mr. Butrus-Ghali? The 
foreign press carries different interpretations of that mandate. 
  [Akashi] I have explained many times to the distinguished 
members of the press that the secretary general has given me a 
mandate to call for NATO air support for self-defense for our 
troops. This is different from air strikes for offensive 
purposes. Neither the secretary general nor I have the right to 
initiate such attacks. Even NATO would have to go back to 
consult the NATO Council to solve that issue, the issue of air 
strikes. 
  We are talking about something specific here, about the air 
support for the self-defense of our troops. 
  [Karadzic] We have completely clarified the issue of 
Srebrenica with Mr. Akashi, General Rose, and their associates, 
and we do not believe that this will be a problem. The Dutch 
troops are already in Srebrenica, and we believe that the 
Canadian UNPROFOR will be completely replaced by the Dutch 
forces by the end of February. 
  As for the opening of the airport in Tuzla, we understand 
the 
efforts of the international community to increase the inflow of 
humanitarian aid into the Tuzla region. Last time we offered 
Mrs. Sadako Ogata, UN High Commissioner for Refugees, to double, 
even treble, the number of humanitarian land convoys, and we are 
ready to increase the inflow of convoys for Tuzla, and that has 
already happened. Larger amounts of food are already reaching 
Tuzla. 
  I am afraid that the issue of opening Tuzla airport could 
become more of a psychological than a realistic one, 
psychological in the sense that the international community 
could, that is, some belligerent members of the international 
community could use this as a form of exerting further pressure. 
We do not reject in principle the notion of it, but it is too 
major a decision for any one Serbian official to make by 
himself. That has to be decided by our assembly. [end recording] 

</TEXT>

