<F P=100> BOSNIA-HERZEGOVINA </F>
<H3> <TI>   French General: Muslims Choose `War Option' </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0102224694 Belgrade TANJUG in English 2203 GMT 1 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0102224694 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> ["Pool" item] </F>
  [Text] Paris, Feb 1 (TANJUG) -- French General Philippe 
Mercier, member of the chief of staff [as received], said on 
Tuesday that Bosnian Muslims have completely turned to the war 
option after they captured arms factories in the latest fighting 
(against Croats) in the central part of the former Yugoslav 
Republic of Bosnia-Herzegovina. 
  Gen. Mercier told the press that, thanks to financial 
support 
of Islamic countries, Bosnian Muslims continue to arm themselves 
because arms and ammuntion, even a certain number of rockets, 
can reach them across borders of the former Yugoslavia despite 
the U.N. embargo on arms deliveries to the former Yugoslavia. 
  This is the first time in France that a high military 
official openly spoke about the amply arming of the Bosnian 
Muslims and the aid they were receiving from Islamic countries. 
  French military sources assessed that Muslim forces loyal to 
Bosnian Muslim leader Alija Izetbegovic numbered around 85,000 
troops, possessed between 20 to 30 tanks, around 350 cannons and 
a score of helicopters and airplanes. 
  Gen. Mercier confirmed reports that "several units" of the 
Croatian Army were in Bosnia-Herzegovina helping Bosnian Croats 
in the fighting against Muslims in central Bosnia-Herzegovina. 
  French sources claim that the forthcoming meeting of the 
European Union foreign ministers, to be held in Brussels on 
February 7, will discuss the possible imposing of economic 
sanctions against Croatia due to its direct military involvement 
in the civil war in Bosnia-Herzegovina. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

