<F P=100> BOSNIA-HERZEGOVINA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Red Cross Aid Convoy Arrives in Zenica </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU0102195094 Paris AFP in English 1923 GMT 1 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU0102195094 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Geneva, Feb 1 (AFP) -- A Red Cross aid convoy 
carrying 186 tonnes of badly needed food and supplies arrived in 
the besieged Bosnian town of Zenica Tuesday [1 February], the 
International Committee of the Red Cross [ICRC] said here. 
  The convoy, the first since December 20, crossed through 
territory held by the besieging Bosnian Serbs under an agreement 
signed on January 27 which gave the ICRC the right to supply 
Zenica regularly. 
  The 10 trucks brought to the town, held by the mainly-Moslem 
Bosnian army, 4,200 litres of fuel oil, 600 litres of kerosene, 
60 tonnes of individual parcels, 96 tonnes of flour, 9,600 
blankets and medical supplies. A second convoy of similar size 
was expected in Zenica Thursday [3 February], the ICRC said. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

