<F P=100> POLAND </F>
<H3> <TI>   Holds News Conference </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0102212494 Warsaw TVP Television First Program Network in 
Polish 1830 GMT 1 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD0102212494 </F>
<F P=104>  Warsaw TVP Television First Program Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Polish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by correspondent Katarzyna Kolenda; relayed by </F>
Polonia TV network] 
  [Text] One day before Prime Minister Pawlak's departure for 
Brussels, a NATO Headquarters information mission arrived in 
Warsaw. 
  [Begin recording of Herman Von Richthofen, German 
representative to NATO, in English with superimposed Polish 
translation] The purpose of our mission is, to a certain extent, 
to demonstrate that NATO is treating the Partnership for Peace 
scheme seriously. We would like to begin political and military 
cooperation within this scheme as soon as possible. [end 
recording] 
  Members of the mission declared that, before the end of this 
year, joint exercises of Polish and NATO armed forces will be 
held. [video cuts to show General Stanislaw Wozniak speaking to 
camera] For the time being, we are not considering the number 
of divisions assigned to the scheme. We are considering the 
possibility of selecting small forces. We are talking here about 
a platoon, a company. 
  An agreement that Prime Minister Waldemar Pawlak will sign 
tomorrow concerns political consent for Poland's participation 
in the scheme. A detailed document is being prepared, and, in 
the view of the Ministry of Foreign Affairs, it will be signed 
in a few weeks' time. It is still not known how much 
participation in the scheme will cost us: This year's budget 
does not envision any expenditure for this purpose. 
  Representatives of the NATO mission discussed Poland's 
participation in the scheme with Foreign Minister Andrzej 
Olechowski and Jerzy Milewski, head of the National Security 
Office. Piotr Kolodziejczyk, the minister of national defense, 
and General Tadeusz Wilecki, head of the General Staff, could 
not meet the NATO delegation because they are on vacation with 
the president in the Karkonosze Mountains. 

</TEXT>

