<F P=100> CROATIA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Serbs Accuse Army of Violating Cease-Fire </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0102215094 Belgrade TANJUG in English 2037 GMT 1 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0102215094 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> ["Pool" item] </F>
  [Text] Knin, Feb 1 (TANJUG) -- Croatia on Monday [31 
January] violated a ceasefire agreement it had concluded with 
the republic of Serb Krajina (R.S.K.), only a day after putting 
its signature on a document extending it to February 28, the 
R.S.K. army command said on Tuesday. Croatian mortars shelled 
Serb villages in the Novigrad hinterland, the R.S.K. army said 
in a statement and added that small arms fire had been reported 
in the areas of Vrlika and Drnis in the south of the R.S.K., and 
in the regions of Lika and western Slavonia. Late last year, 
the R.S.K. and Croatia had agreed to observe a ceasefire during 
Christmas. The agreement was first extended on January 13, and 
again on Sunday. The latest extension was mediated by U.N. 
peace-keepers. 
  The R.S.K. was proclaimed by Serbs in late 1991 within their 
ethnic and historic boundaries in parts of the former Yugoslav 
Republic of Croatia, in response to Croatia's violent secession 
from the former Yugoslav Federation and attempt to downgrade the 
Serbs to an ethnic minority. The R.S.K. was placed under U.N. 
protection in March of 1992, but this has not prevented Croatia 
from attacking it three times since in an attempt to impose its 
rule there by force. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-30365 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "dreeu022_k_94004" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-EEU-94-022 </AU>
Document Type:Daily Report 
<DATE1>  2 Feb 1994 </DATE1>

