<H3> <TI>   Zieleniec, Finnish Counterpart Meet in Prague </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0102155494 Prague Radiozurnal Radio Network in Czech 1300 
GMT 1 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD0102155494 </F>
<F P=104>  Prague Radiozurnal Radio Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Czech </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Finnish Foreign Affairs Minister Heikki Haavisto is 
paying a working visit to Prague today. After consultations 
with his Czech counterpart, Josef Zieleniec, the Scandinavian 
guest met journalists at Cernin Palace. Miroslav Konvalina 
reports: 
  [Konvalina] Haavisto stressed at the briefing that he talked 
with Josef Zieleniec, above all, about the security political 
situation in Europe and about bilateral relations, which he 
designated as very good. He said that Finland, just as Austria, 
Norway, and Sweden, should soon become a member of the European 
Union, where it will seek its security guarantees. Finland is 
not interested in entering NATO or any other security 
structures. It considers the Partnership for Peace, however, a 
good initiative for East European countries. 
  In an interview for Radiozurnal, Haavisto praised the work 
of 
the Czech Republic in the Security Council. 

</TEXT>

